A report on the assessment of the Presidential Amnesty Programme (PAP) in the Niger Delta region has been launched. According to Nextier SDP,  which  commissioned the report, the assessment was necessitated by the need to develop actionable recommendations on how to transition the agency into a vehicle that will be able to address the key issues of the Niger Delta region more effectively. The report suggested four transition options for the PAP as the programme winds down. The four options include, closure of the programme over a short time frame of nine months, ensuring that all registered beneficiaries complete their reintegration programme with the period; Devolution of PAP Activities to Federal MDAs; Transforming PAP into an Anonymous Youth Programme, which would not just be focused on militant youth but youth as a whole; and Devolving PAP Activities to State Oil Development Commission The report recommended that to address feelings of exclusion from PAP which has made violence a recurring decimal in the Niger Delta, the plight of excluded active youth, women and ravaged communities must be factored into the transition or exit strategy of PAP It also recommended that innovative strategies must be used to get jobs for those who have been trained in order to prevent them from relapse into violent crimes as well effective oversight functions, deployment of robust monitoring and evaluation mechanisms to curb corruption Speaking during the launch of the report in Abuja, Hon Henry Nwauba, Deputy Chairman, House of Representatives Committee on Niger Delta said the PAP needs to be looked into in a holistic manner to evaluated the progress that have been made. He however called for stakeholders engagement to avoid an exist strategy that will lead to renew violence in the Niger Delta. 